00:00:25.830 --> 00:00:30.600
PROFESSOR: We ended last time
kind of without really a

00:00:30.600 --> 00:00:36.760
resolution in the sense that we
looked at this example of

00:00:36.760 --> 00:00:46.030
these vendors in India and the
Philippines, and these vendors

00:00:46.030 --> 00:00:48.295
were somehow--

00:00:50.850 --> 00:00:55.630
they seem to be unable to save
their way out of something

00:00:55.630 --> 00:01:01.960
that seems extremely costly
to keep bearing.

00:01:01.960 --> 00:01:13.310
They were paying 5% a day, and
even when somebody paid down

00:01:13.310 --> 00:01:17.800
their entire debt so that they
didn't have to borrow any

00:01:17.800 --> 00:01:22.170
more, they slipped back into
debt within about three weeks.

00:01:22.170 --> 00:01:32.060
So it was a sense in which these
people seem to find it

00:01:32.060 --> 00:01:40.140
difficult to stay out of debt
and, in particular, to hold

00:01:40.140 --> 00:01:41.520
onto their savings.

00:01:44.300 --> 00:01:49.960
So here's another experiment,
which sort of brings out some

00:01:49.960 --> 00:01:51.205
more off it.

00:01:51.205 --> 00:01:55.900
It's in Busia, Kenya, a
letter missing there.

00:02:01.610 --> 00:02:06.870
So the way it started
is that--

00:02:09.550 --> 00:02:16.370
the experiment is by Esther
Duflo, Michael Kremer, and

00:02:16.370 --> 00:02:17.630
John Robinson.

00:02:17.630 --> 00:02:21.260
What they had done was they
started by actually giving

00:02:21.260 --> 00:02:24.590
farmers some fertilizer.

00:02:24.590 --> 00:02:28.600
One of the enduring kind of
puzzles in agricultural and

00:02:28.600 --> 00:02:33.090
economics is why farmers in
Africa don't use more

00:02:33.090 --> 00:02:36.700
fertilizer given that fertilizer
is something that

00:02:36.700 --> 00:02:40.600
basically makes money
for people.

00:02:40.600 --> 00:02:43.860
So why don't they use
fertilizer, and their various

00:02:43.860 --> 00:02:46.000
possible answers would
talk about those.

00:02:46.000 --> 00:02:52.605
But to demonstrate that it
really does seem to work--

00:02:59.070 --> 00:03:01.190
what they started by doing is
making sure that it's true

00:03:01.190 --> 00:03:09.400
that it works, so what they did
was they had people give

00:03:09.400 --> 00:03:15.610
farmers fertilizer and told
them, this is your plot, just

00:03:15.610 --> 00:03:17.790
go ahead and use fertilizer,
and they give them free

00:03:17.790 --> 00:03:18.510
fertilizer.

00:03:18.510 --> 00:03:20.990
So they took a bunch of plots
and gave them free fertilizer.

00:03:23.800 --> 00:03:27.040
So very simple, you give people
free fertilizer, they

00:03:27.040 --> 00:03:34.010
do use it, not surprisingly,
especially if you make sure

00:03:34.010 --> 00:03:36.560
they can't sell it, and
they do use it.

00:03:36.560 --> 00:03:50.150
When they use it,
their incomes go

00:03:50.150 --> 00:04:05.320
up by 27%, and that's--

00:04:09.620 --> 00:04:13.360
Oh, their incomes go
up by 27%, which is

00:04:13.360 --> 00:04:15.340
100% increase annually.

00:04:15.340 --> 00:04:19.410
So that's like three months,
three months, you bought the

00:04:19.410 --> 00:04:23.310
fertilizer, you laid it in the
ground, you waited for three

00:04:23.310 --> 00:04:27.100
months, you would get
27% more back.

00:04:27.100 --> 00:04:33.630
So they were pretty convinced
that fertilizer was a very

00:04:33.630 --> 00:04:35.510
useful thing to use.

00:04:35.510 --> 00:04:38.500
And this, they did it many
times, so it varies.

00:04:38.500 --> 00:04:41.980
Fertilizer is, in fact,
not predictable.

00:04:41.980 --> 00:04:47.590
Sometimes it works better than
others, but the range of these

00:04:47.590 --> 00:04:53.360
returns, where you never got
less than 80%, I think,

00:04:53.360 --> 00:04:56.710
basically, on your money, and
that's a very good investment

00:04:56.710 --> 00:04:59.400
if you get 80% on your money.

00:04:59.400 --> 00:05:03.620
Sometimes, you get 500%, but
even if you got a 80% on your

00:05:03.620 --> 00:05:05.370
money, that would be
a good investment.

00:05:05.370 --> 00:05:06.760
So question is why
don't they do it?

00:05:13.250 --> 00:05:15.500
So the various theories,
obviously, on why

00:05:15.500 --> 00:05:17.110
people don't do it.

00:05:17.110 --> 00:05:20.200
One is that they don't
know about it.

00:05:20.200 --> 00:05:24.350
That seems implausible, partly
because fertilizer's not a new

00:05:24.350 --> 00:05:24.720
technology.

00:05:24.720 --> 00:05:26.950
It's been around for
a very long time.

00:05:29.690 --> 00:05:35.380
And second, because take those
farmers who were given free

00:05:35.380 --> 00:05:36.590
fertilizer.

00:05:36.590 --> 00:05:43.440
They used it, they got 100%
return, annualized return, go

00:05:43.440 --> 00:05:47.900
back to those people at the
end of the year and the

00:05:47.900 --> 00:05:51.350
beginning of next season and
ask them do you want to use

00:05:51.350 --> 00:05:53.680
fertilizer.

00:05:53.680 --> 00:05:58.530
98% say yes, of course, we
want to use fertilizer.

00:05:58.530 --> 00:06:02.460
Only 37% actually use it.

00:06:02.460 --> 00:06:06.010
So these are people who clearly
know fertilizer works

00:06:06.010 --> 00:06:07.475
because they did it.

00:06:07.475 --> 00:06:08.725
It worked.

00:06:10.900 --> 00:06:13.990
There's no two ways about the
fact that they know it

00:06:13.990 --> 00:06:17.500
because, the fertilizer, they
had used it, they saw the

00:06:17.500 --> 00:06:20.550
results, they saw
it's working.

00:06:20.550 --> 00:06:24.630
Why didn't the farmers who had
seen that the fertilizer

00:06:24.630 --> 00:06:28.210
generates these massive returns
not go back to using

00:06:28.210 --> 00:06:30.440
fertilizer?

00:06:30.440 --> 00:06:30.850
Yeah?

00:06:30.850 --> 00:06:33.730
AUDIENCE: Beause they said
couldn't really afford it, and

00:06:33.730 --> 00:06:36.694
then also the fact was when
they did have the money,

00:06:36.694 --> 00:06:38.670
fertilizer generally
wasn't there.

00:06:38.670 --> 00:06:42.128
And when they didn't have
the money it was there.

00:06:42.128 --> 00:06:43.610
So it's difficult.

00:06:43.610 --> 00:06:47.590
PROFESSOR: OK, so that's
sort of the--

00:06:47.590 --> 00:06:50.770
but before we come there,
lets rule out some other

00:06:50.770 --> 00:06:51.830
explanations.

00:06:51.830 --> 00:07:00.990
So one other explanation is
credit constraint, so we

00:07:00.990 --> 00:07:03.390
already discussed it's hard
for the poor to borrow.

00:07:03.390 --> 00:07:07.110
Interest rates are very high.

00:07:07.110 --> 00:07:12.780
That would be a good explanation
if fertilizer were

00:07:12.780 --> 00:07:16.020
indivisible, so if you had to
use a certain minimal amount

00:07:16.020 --> 00:07:17.900
to make money.

00:07:17.900 --> 00:07:20.240
But fertilizer is extremely
divisible.

00:07:20.240 --> 00:07:25.550
You can buy it in like You could
buy 500 grams of it, put

00:07:25.550 --> 00:07:29.500
it on a small plot, and
you'll make more money

00:07:29.500 --> 00:07:30.740
on that small plot.

00:07:30.740 --> 00:07:33.720
If you bought two kilos,
you make more

00:07:33.720 --> 00:07:35.080
money on a bigger plot.

00:07:35.080 --> 00:07:37.050
If you bought 10 kilos,
you'd have even more.

00:07:37.050 --> 00:07:42.290
So the question is why don't
people use fertilizer?

00:07:42.290 --> 00:07:45.190
If they have less money,
why don't they use it

00:07:45.190 --> 00:07:46.440
on a smaller plot?

00:07:48.700 --> 00:07:52.120
It's not enough to say that they
don't have money because

00:07:52.120 --> 00:07:54.175
money just--

00:07:54.175 --> 00:07:59.400
if you're less money, you
can use it on less land.

00:07:59.400 --> 00:08:01.840
The main point is that whenever
you use it, you make

00:08:01.840 --> 00:08:08.170
money, so even if you use it on
a smaller plot, the output

00:08:08.170 --> 00:08:11.110
on that plot would still go up
by a lot, and the returns

00:08:11.110 --> 00:08:14.860
would be 100% a year on
the money you put in.

00:08:14.860 --> 00:08:15.800
Yeah?

00:08:15.800 --> 00:08:18.774
AUDIENCE: So I understand what
you're saying, but on the

00:08:18.774 --> 00:08:23.020
other hand, they can only afford
to fertilize a very

00:08:23.020 --> 00:08:26.172
small amount of land, that their
returns might just not

00:08:26.172 --> 00:08:29.325
be worth it to make this
tiny investment.

00:08:29.325 --> 00:08:32.720
You would have to wait for
several months to get an extra

00:08:32.720 --> 00:08:35.387
several rupees whereas you have
this money now, you might

00:08:35.387 --> 00:08:37.085
as well spend it now
[INAUDIBLE].

00:08:39.846 --> 00:08:45.330
PROFESSOR: I guess that might
be right, but it's sort of--

00:08:45.330 --> 00:08:50.600
in the end, it's why aren't they
thinking, look, it's 100

00:08:50.600 --> 00:08:52.260
Kenyan shillings now.

00:08:52.260 --> 00:08:55.950
I'm going to get 200
in three months.

00:08:55.950 --> 00:08:58.300
If it's 100 shillings, and
that's very little, that's a

00:08:58.300 --> 00:09:02.220
dollar and a bit, it's still
you get twice as much.

00:09:02.220 --> 00:09:05.610
So why aren't people thinking
in proportion?

00:09:05.610 --> 00:09:09.870
Why aren't they thinking that
twice as much is a lot more?

00:09:09.870 --> 00:09:10.170
Yeah?

00:09:10.170 --> 00:09:14.130
AUDIENCE: Wouldn't fertilizer
be more viable for bigger

00:09:14.130 --> 00:09:17.100
farmers because they have
irrigation, which is required

00:09:17.100 --> 00:09:18.590
for fertilizer to really work.

00:09:18.590 --> 00:09:20.280
PROFESSOR: Not in
Kenya, actually.

00:09:20.280 --> 00:09:22.410
I mean, fertilizer is--

00:09:22.410 --> 00:09:24.880
it's true that it would
be more useful.

00:09:24.880 --> 00:09:29.610
But mostly even, Kenya
has especially--

00:09:29.610 --> 00:09:34.280
this is the what they call
the short rain season.

00:09:34.280 --> 00:09:38.570
Most of agriculture in the short
rain season is rain fed,

00:09:38.570 --> 00:09:41.400
so I think people don't--

00:09:41.400 --> 00:09:45.600
it's true that I'm sure
fertilizer would reduce risk,

00:09:45.600 --> 00:09:48.680
but there isn't much of risk.

00:09:48.680 --> 00:09:54.150
Even when the rains are not
great, you still make money.

00:09:54.150 --> 00:09:59.100
So if you ask farmers, they do
tell you the answer that they

00:09:59.100 --> 00:10:00.350
don't have any money.

00:10:06.020 --> 00:10:09.430
So they're answer is we
don't have any money.

00:10:09.430 --> 00:10:11.090
It's exactly what you
said, which is that

00:10:11.090 --> 00:10:12.360
they don't have money.

00:10:12.360 --> 00:10:14.200
Well, how would we
buy fertilizer?

00:10:14.200 --> 00:10:17.890
The fact is that, as you'll see
in a minute, they do have

00:10:17.890 --> 00:10:25.320
money, especially when
they harvest.

00:10:25.320 --> 00:10:28.780
Farming is a cyclical
business.

00:10:28.780 --> 00:10:30.940
You make money at some point.

00:10:30.940 --> 00:10:34.820
You plant, you wait for three
months, your crops come out,

00:10:34.820 --> 00:10:37.330
you sell your crops,
you get money, then

00:10:37.330 --> 00:10:40.030
you wait for a while.

00:10:40.030 --> 00:10:42.690
You buy some seeds.

00:10:42.690 --> 00:10:45.040
You plant again, so it's
kind of a cycle.

00:10:45.040 --> 00:10:49.640
So if you think of the point
when they have sold the crops,

00:10:49.640 --> 00:10:52.920
they certainly, at that point,
certainly do have money.

00:10:52.920 --> 00:10:55.090
It's not true that they don't,
and we'll see in a minute

00:10:55.090 --> 00:10:57.210
evidence that they
do have money.

00:10:57.210 --> 00:11:01.570
And in particular,
they seem to--

00:11:01.570 --> 00:11:03.620
I mean, even if they can't save
all of it because they

00:11:03.620 --> 00:11:08.090
need to eat most of it, they
could have saved a little bit

00:11:08.090 --> 00:11:13.390
of it, so they could have
saved the money.

00:11:13.390 --> 00:11:17.030
Alternatively, they could just
buy fertilizer then, when they

00:11:17.030 --> 00:11:17.710
have the money.

00:11:17.710 --> 00:11:19.330
Fertilizer it is very durable.

00:11:19.330 --> 00:11:21.600
You just buy fertilizer.

00:11:21.600 --> 00:11:23.320
You keep it in a bag.

00:11:23.320 --> 00:11:25.050
It'll stay for three months.

00:11:25.050 --> 00:11:28.190
It's not that you need to buy
fertilizer on the day when you

00:11:28.190 --> 00:11:29.430
need to go farming.

00:11:29.430 --> 00:11:33.200
You could have bought fertilizer
ahead of time and

00:11:33.200 --> 00:11:36.640
kept it in your home.

00:11:36.640 --> 00:11:40.140
So we'll see that they do have
money at some point, and when

00:11:40.140 --> 00:11:42.040
they do have money, they
don't necessarily buy

00:11:42.040 --> 00:11:43.290
fertilizer with it.

00:11:51.290 --> 00:11:55.530
In fact, they did a small
survey, and they asked did you

00:11:55.530 --> 00:12:02.200
buy fertilizer at harvest
time when you had money.

00:12:02.200 --> 00:12:05.890
The answer is, no, almost
no one did that.

00:12:05.890 --> 00:12:11.960
So if you look at the
population, about 30% of them

00:12:11.960 --> 00:12:20.970
use fertilizer at any point of
time, but of that 30%, only

00:12:20.970 --> 00:12:24.650
about 3% had bought it early
when they had money.

00:12:24.650 --> 00:12:29.850
Most of them bought it at the
point of planting, so they had

00:12:29.850 --> 00:12:31.620
either managed to save
or they had borrowed.

00:12:31.620 --> 00:12:33.390
But in any case, they had--

00:12:33.390 --> 00:12:34.730
[INAUDIBLE]

00:12:34.730 --> 00:12:36.125
Let me remove Skype.

00:12:56.260 --> 00:12:57.510
Yep.

00:13:00.440 --> 00:13:11.130
So what is true is that, so
basically, no one buys

00:13:11.130 --> 00:13:13.620
fertilizer early even though--

00:13:16.280 --> 00:13:19.970
if you think that it's
a problem to--

00:13:19.970 --> 00:13:25.760
maybe you don't have money at
planting time, then you should

00:13:25.760 --> 00:13:27.900
just buy it early.

00:13:27.900 --> 00:13:34.460
So here's a nice experiment,
which is sort of exactly

00:13:34.460 --> 00:13:37.590
trying to figure out what's
going on here.

00:13:42.040 --> 00:13:47.830
So what they did was they went
to different farmers, and

00:13:47.830 --> 00:13:51.730
since some farmers had already
had some experience using

00:13:51.730 --> 00:13:56.495
fertilizer and others had not,
they stratified by that.

00:13:56.495 --> 00:13:57.745
What does it mean to stratify?

00:14:01.650 --> 00:14:02.900
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

00:14:13.650 --> 00:14:16.430
PROFESSOR: Right, they're
randomized within the group of

00:14:16.430 --> 00:14:20.870
people who had used it before,
and within the group of people

00:14:20.870 --> 00:14:22.050
who had used it before.

00:14:22.050 --> 00:14:27.850
So they divided up the
population and randomized

00:14:27.850 --> 00:14:32.650
within each group, and then they
came to the household and

00:14:32.650 --> 00:14:38.970
offered them fertilizer and
said, look, you pay for it.

00:14:38.970 --> 00:14:43.742
We will sell it to you, and
we'll bring it to you so you

00:14:43.742 --> 00:14:45.770
don't have to go to a
market to buy it.

00:14:45.770 --> 00:14:53.110
And that saves a trip, saves
trouble, but it also--

00:14:53.110 --> 00:14:57.910
so this was done at harvest
time, and it basically forced

00:14:57.910 --> 00:15:01.650
them to make a decision then.

00:15:01.650 --> 00:15:04.530
So you couldn't say, well,
maybe I'll buy it.

00:15:04.530 --> 00:15:05.390
Maybe I won't.

00:15:05.390 --> 00:15:09.885
I'll wait until when
I need it.

00:15:09.885 --> 00:15:13.160
It was kind of a all or nothing
decision, where they

00:15:13.160 --> 00:15:20.880
had to take a decision right
now when they had money.

00:15:20.880 --> 00:15:22.130
This was the first experiment.

00:15:28.040 --> 00:15:33.210
Then they follow it up a second
experiment where they

00:15:33.210 --> 00:15:40.950
took another set of people,
and then in the second

00:15:40.950 --> 00:15:43.995
experiment, they offered people
an additional choice.

00:15:47.050 --> 00:15:53.120
You can either choose
when you'll get--

00:15:53.120 --> 00:15:54.390
we'll come to sell
you fertilizer.

00:15:57.510 --> 00:16:02.570
This was done before harvest, so
they didn't have any money

00:16:02.570 --> 00:16:03.620
at that time.

00:16:03.620 --> 00:16:08.250
So they said you can either tell
us, and we'll come right

00:16:08.250 --> 00:16:11.840
after harvest, or we'll
come when you plant.

00:16:11.840 --> 00:16:14.550
Just tell us what to do.

00:16:14.550 --> 00:16:17.330
So the first experiment, they
were not given the choice.

00:16:17.330 --> 00:16:20.190
They said you want it now, we'll
bring it to you free.

00:16:20.190 --> 00:16:21.920
You don't have to go collect.

00:16:21.920 --> 00:16:24.610
If not, that's it.

00:16:24.610 --> 00:16:27.030
Then you're on your own.

00:16:27.030 --> 00:16:32.280
Now, it's you can either
buy now or later.

00:16:32.280 --> 00:16:33.530
You're offered a choice.

00:16:37.810 --> 00:16:46.660
And the other thing that they
did was other people who were

00:16:46.660 --> 00:16:51.620
not given any offer like this,
when it came to the actual

00:16:51.620 --> 00:16:54.410
time of the planting, they came
to these people and said

00:16:54.410 --> 00:16:56.620
do you want to buy fertilizer.

00:16:56.620 --> 00:17:01.890
We'll bring it to you, and then
some people, they offered

00:17:01.890 --> 00:17:04.760
a 50% discount.

00:17:04.760 --> 00:17:08.410
So they actually said if
we give you a discount,

00:17:08.410 --> 00:17:09.680
will you buy it?

00:17:09.680 --> 00:17:12.089
So these were the treatments, so
think of the treatments as

00:17:12.089 --> 00:17:17.130
the first treatment, all or
nothing at harvest time, you

00:17:17.130 --> 00:17:22.790
want to buy fertilizer; second
treatment, before harvest, do

00:17:22.790 --> 00:17:27.250
you want to buy fertilizer at
harvest or later; third

00:17:27.250 --> 00:17:32.180
treatment, at planting time, do
you want to buy fertilizer

00:17:32.180 --> 00:17:36.260
from us if we deliver
it to you free.

00:17:36.260 --> 00:17:37.510
That's the experiment.

00:17:43.590 --> 00:17:50.160
Before we get into
the experiment,

00:17:50.160 --> 00:17:53.540
suppose people were--

00:17:53.540 --> 00:17:56.420
what's the disadvantage
of saying that you

00:17:56.420 --> 00:17:58.930
can only buy it--

00:17:58.930 --> 00:18:02.370
we'll offer it to you
now, but not later?

00:18:02.370 --> 00:18:05.130
What's the downside of that?

00:18:05.130 --> 00:18:07.530
Why did they go to the second
treatment, do you think, where

00:18:07.530 --> 00:18:15.500
they give you a choice
when to buy?

00:18:15.500 --> 00:18:17.683
What's the advantage of giving
you this choice?

00:18:32.966 --> 00:18:33.459
Yeah?

00:18:33.459 --> 00:18:34.709
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]?

00:18:38.890 --> 00:18:45.510
PROFESSOR: Right, exactly, I
mean, typically we think that

00:18:45.510 --> 00:18:48.560
buying things early
is a bad idea.

00:18:48.560 --> 00:18:48.900
Why?

00:18:48.900 --> 00:18:52.240
Because you're locking
up your money.

00:18:52.240 --> 00:18:57.130
I mean, fertilizer's not that
easy to sell, whereas if

00:18:57.130 --> 00:19:00.130
somebody got sick, you
had money, you'd

00:19:00.130 --> 00:19:02.490
be able to buy medicine.

00:19:02.490 --> 00:19:04.180
Now, instead you have
fertilizer.

00:19:04.180 --> 00:19:05.710
So why would you
lock up money?

00:19:05.710 --> 00:19:09.740
So in general, the standard
intuition would be that

00:19:09.740 --> 00:19:13.670
locking up money is a bad
idea, not a good idea.

00:19:13.670 --> 00:19:14.970
So in the first treatment,
they were

00:19:14.970 --> 00:19:16.310
forced to lock up money.

00:19:16.310 --> 00:19:17.870
The second one, they
give them a choice.

00:19:23.280 --> 00:19:33.390
So we take the first one,
basically, there was a 50%--

00:19:33.390 --> 00:19:39.860
so about, as I said, 25% to 30%
of them use fertilizer.

00:19:39.860 --> 00:19:44.340
That went up by 11 to 14
percentage points, so that's

00:19:44.340 --> 00:19:49.460
like a 46% to 63% increase
in fertilizer use.

00:19:49.460 --> 00:19:54.050
So you get more than 50%, more
than 50% increase in

00:19:54.050 --> 00:19:57.785
fertilizer use when you just
tell people, look, we'll bring

00:19:57.785 --> 00:20:00.760
it to you for free.

00:20:00.760 --> 00:20:02.910
Do you want it at
harvest time?

00:20:07.560 --> 00:20:10.790
This did not change--

00:20:10.790 --> 00:20:15.720
so then what they looked at is
this season, of course, you

00:20:15.720 --> 00:20:18.200
getting it delivered to
you, so you buy it.

00:20:21.140 --> 00:20:23.260
It doesn't have any
persistent effect.

00:20:23.260 --> 00:20:24.790
You saw that it was
a good idea.

00:20:24.790 --> 00:20:28.220
Did you start saving money
or finding a way to

00:20:28.220 --> 00:20:30.040
buy ahead of time?

00:20:30.040 --> 00:20:31.820
The answer's no.

00:20:31.820 --> 00:20:33.150
People seem to be--

00:20:33.150 --> 00:20:39.440
when you offer it to them for
free at harvest time, a

00:20:39.440 --> 00:20:41.430
substantial number
of them buy it.

00:20:41.430 --> 00:20:45.780
But if you said, look, last
year you did this,

00:20:45.780 --> 00:20:47.040
look, it was good.

00:20:47.040 --> 00:20:49.800
You got much more output.

00:20:49.800 --> 00:20:54.010
This time, why don't you
buy on your own?

00:20:54.010 --> 00:20:55.120
Just buy it at harvest time.

00:20:55.120 --> 00:20:56.630
We won't help you.

00:20:56.630 --> 00:20:58.210
You can do it on your own.

00:20:58.210 --> 00:20:59.760
Nobody does it.

00:20:59.760 --> 00:21:02.690
So it's not the case that
people learn from this

00:21:02.690 --> 00:21:08.060
experience to buy fertilizer
to use at harvest time.

00:21:08.060 --> 00:21:10.725
They go back to not using
it, basically.

00:21:20.120 --> 00:21:25.820
So when you give people a
choice, that's experiment two,

00:21:25.820 --> 00:21:26.970
you get bigger effects.

00:21:26.970 --> 00:21:30.550
Instead of getting 11 to 14
percentage points, you get 18

00:21:30.550 --> 00:21:31.940
percentage points.

00:21:31.940 --> 00:21:42.040
That's almost 75% increase in
fertilizer use, so if you give

00:21:42.040 --> 00:21:45.040
them a choice, then you get
more people taking it up.

00:21:49.010 --> 00:21:52.160
On the other hand, if you show
up at harvest time--

00:21:52.160 --> 00:21:57.680
so this is not mainly an effect
of offering it to them,

00:21:57.680 --> 00:21:59.240
just bringing it to them.

00:21:59.240 --> 00:22:01.490
It's not because they're getting
free transportation.

00:22:01.490 --> 00:22:03.990
It's not because they don't have
to go buy it that they're

00:22:03.990 --> 00:22:08.130
doing it because if you came to
them at planting time and

00:22:08.130 --> 00:22:13.310
said do you want to buy it,
we'll get it to you free, that

00:22:13.310 --> 00:22:14.560
has no impact.

00:22:17.710 --> 00:22:23.650
If you bring it to people at
planting time free, then they

00:22:23.650 --> 00:22:26.720
don't buy it, so it's not the
case that you get the same

00:22:26.720 --> 00:22:30.560
effect by just delivering it
to them free at any time.

00:22:30.560 --> 00:22:32.450
You have to deliver
it to them free

00:22:32.450 --> 00:22:36.940
typically at planting time--

00:22:36.940 --> 00:22:38.710
sorry, at harvest time.

00:22:38.710 --> 00:22:41.190
When they have money, you have
to deliver it to them free,

00:22:41.190 --> 00:22:43.830
then they buy it.

00:22:43.830 --> 00:22:47.280
If you bring it to them when
they are planting, and you

00:22:47.280 --> 00:22:50.240
offer free delivery, that
doesn't have the same impact.

00:22:50.240 --> 00:22:52.520
So it's not that whenever
you offer it to them

00:22:52.520 --> 00:22:56.800
free, they buy a lot.

00:22:56.800 --> 00:22:59.030
They only buy a lot if
you offer it free

00:22:59.030 --> 00:23:00.280
when they have money.

00:23:05.410 --> 00:23:13.310
The 50% discount does have a
significant effect, maybe not

00:23:13.310 --> 00:23:14.520
surprisingly.

00:23:14.520 --> 00:23:19.480
On the other hand, it's not
really smaller than just

00:23:19.480 --> 00:23:25.680
offering people to get free
delivery with no discount.

00:23:25.680 --> 00:23:28.650
No discount is better than
giving people a discount if

00:23:28.650 --> 00:23:31.270
you give them the discount
at the right time--

00:23:31.270 --> 00:23:33.360
sorry, the free--

00:23:33.360 --> 00:23:35.750
the delivery at the
right time.

00:23:35.750 --> 00:23:41.640
So if I go to you at harvest
time, and I say I won't give

00:23:41.640 --> 00:23:44.490
you a discount, when do you
want it, you get a bigger

00:23:44.490 --> 00:23:48.980
effect than if I tell you I'll
give you 50% discount, but

00:23:48.980 --> 00:23:55.820
that I offer that to you
only at planting time.

00:23:55.820 --> 00:23:58.780
So just those magnitudes are
what's worth looking at

00:23:58.780 --> 00:24:01.600
because you're getting
people--

00:24:01.600 --> 00:24:08.180
it's not that people, even if
you offer them a 50% discount,

00:24:08.180 --> 00:24:11.790
you don't get as big an effect
as just finding the right time

00:24:11.790 --> 00:24:13.835
to make an offer without
a discount.

00:24:17.551 --> 00:24:18.044
Yeah?

00:24:18.044 --> 00:24:21.970
AUDIENCE: How do people get this
if it wasn't delivered?

00:24:21.970 --> 00:24:25.300
PROFESSOR: You just go to the
local town and you buy--

00:24:25.300 --> 00:24:27.188
AUDIENCE: --drag it back
or pull it back--

00:24:27.188 --> 00:24:29.140
PROFESSOR: Oh, you
bring it on a--

00:24:29.140 --> 00:24:33.520
they have all these three-wheel
taxis and little

00:24:33.520 --> 00:24:35.040
trucks in Kenya.

00:24:35.040 --> 00:24:38.470
You put it in the back of
one, and you bring it.

00:24:38.470 --> 00:24:38.970
It's like--

00:24:38.970 --> 00:24:41.240
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]?

00:24:41.240 --> 00:24:44.090
PROFESSOR: No, it's a small
cost, actually.

00:24:44.090 --> 00:24:45.340
That's the usual.

00:24:47.510 --> 00:24:50.010
Now, you notice that
there was this 18

00:24:50.010 --> 00:24:52.880
percentage point increase.

00:24:52.880 --> 00:24:58.800
That came from a bunch of those
people said, look, it's

00:24:58.800 --> 00:25:06.230
free delivery, but
we just want it

00:25:06.230 --> 00:25:08.590
delivered at planting time.

00:25:11.730 --> 00:25:18.760
So some people behaved as if
they had no worries about

00:25:18.760 --> 00:25:23.290
having the money later, and the
other half said bring it

00:25:23.290 --> 00:25:26.930
to us now, so a bunch
of people said

00:25:26.930 --> 00:25:28.180
bring it to us now.

00:25:31.520 --> 00:25:35.790
The reason why this one gives
you a bigger effect than

00:25:35.790 --> 00:25:40.230
forcing people to buy early is
because a bunch of those

00:25:40.230 --> 00:25:43.080
people actually prefer
to get it late.

00:25:43.080 --> 00:25:45.870
So it's clear that the economics
we described before

00:25:45.870 --> 00:25:49.380
is working for some people, but
it's also striking that

00:25:49.380 --> 00:25:52.940
about half of those people
say, no, we want it now.

00:25:52.940 --> 00:25:54.970
We want to lock up our money.

00:25:54.970 --> 00:25:58.060
We want our money to
not be spendable.

00:25:58.060 --> 00:26:00.370
We want it in fertilizer now.

00:26:00.370 --> 00:26:04.590
So what's quite striking is
that people are willing to

00:26:04.590 --> 00:26:07.340
lock up their money,
even though it's--

00:26:14.370 --> 00:26:16.030
So what could be going on?

00:26:24.710 --> 00:26:31.500
So here's a story that
seems to mostly work.

00:26:31.500 --> 00:26:33.890
So these people have money
at harvest time and want

00:26:33.890 --> 00:26:37.310
fertilizer, but somehow, they
don't manage to buy

00:26:37.310 --> 00:26:38.900
fertilizer.

00:26:38.900 --> 00:26:46.170
So the reason why the experiment
works is that these

00:26:46.170 --> 00:26:49.746
people basically say, look,
we will buy fertilizer.

00:26:58.910 --> 00:27:06.690
So what seems to be going on
is that, as we said, 98% of

00:27:06.690 --> 00:27:11.050
those people who had plots where
fertilizer was used said

00:27:11.050 --> 00:27:12.500
they wanted to buy it again.

00:27:12.500 --> 00:27:14.970
Only 37% actually did.

00:27:14.970 --> 00:27:18.490
So at harvest time, it seems
most people plan to use

00:27:18.490 --> 00:27:22.390
fertilizer, and then only
a small fraction of them

00:27:22.390 --> 00:27:24.470
actually managed to get there.

00:27:24.470 --> 00:27:29.310
So what seems to happen
is that they

00:27:29.310 --> 00:27:31.180
don't manage to implement.

00:27:31.180 --> 00:27:35.730
So they think that they're going
to buy fertilizer, but

00:27:35.730 --> 00:27:38.710
then somehow end up spending the
money before they get to

00:27:38.710 --> 00:27:39.960
the fertilizer.

00:27:45.110 --> 00:27:51.600
So one way to think about what
could be happening is that

00:27:51.600 --> 00:27:59.240
people say, look, today I really
want to buy fertilizer,

00:27:59.240 --> 00:28:05.160
but right now, I really like a
drink or I'd really like to

00:28:05.160 --> 00:28:06.430
have a barbecue.

00:28:06.430 --> 00:28:09.250
So they go to the market, they
buy something, and they say,

00:28:09.250 --> 00:28:12.220
look, it doesn't really matter
because tomorrow,

00:28:12.220 --> 00:28:13.470
I'm going to save.

00:28:17.320 --> 00:28:22.610
Today, let me have a barbecue,
but tomorrow, I'm definitely

00:28:22.610 --> 00:28:23.850
going to save.

00:28:23.850 --> 00:28:27.470
So they say that so it doesn't
really matter.

00:28:27.470 --> 00:28:31.970
It's going to be in three months
that we're going to

00:28:31.970 --> 00:28:35.040
plant, so even if I don't save
today, I'll save tomorrow.

00:28:40.320 --> 00:28:45.270
So sometimes, this is
represented by this formula.

00:28:45.270 --> 00:28:47.710
These kind of preferences are
sometimes [INAUDIBLE]

00:28:47.710 --> 00:28:50.360
by this formula.

00:28:50.360 --> 00:28:56.040
So the U function is the
utility you get or the

00:28:56.040 --> 00:28:59.160
pleasure you get out
of eating today or

00:28:59.160 --> 00:29:01.330
tomorrow or day after.

00:29:01.330 --> 00:29:07.330
Today is c0, tomorrow's c1, day
after is c2, the day after

00:29:07.330 --> 00:29:08.480
that is c3.

00:29:08.480 --> 00:29:13.130
Or we could think of months,
c0 this month, c1 is next

00:29:13.130 --> 00:29:15.886
month, et cetera.

00:29:15.886 --> 00:29:20.830
What's important is that U of
c1 is multiplied by two

00:29:20.830 --> 00:29:22.876
numbers, both less than 1.

00:29:26.208 --> 00:29:30.730
U of c2 is multiplied by
beta delta squared.

00:29:30.730 --> 00:29:34.570
If delta's less than 1, delta
squared is less than 1, but I

00:29:34.570 --> 00:29:36.810
didn't multiply by beta
squared delta squared.

00:29:36.810 --> 00:29:40.150
I multiplied by beta
delta squared.

00:29:40.150 --> 00:29:46.150
The day after that is multiplied
by beta delta

00:29:46.150 --> 00:29:51.440
cubed, so I didn't multiply
by beta cubed delta cubed.

00:29:51.440 --> 00:29:53.610
Why am I doing that?

00:29:53.610 --> 00:29:58.610
What's the point being made
by having that structure?

00:29:58.610 --> 00:30:01.860
This is sometimes called a
quasi hyperbolic model.

00:30:06.380 --> 00:30:07.995
Why did I put that
structure there?

00:30:28.080 --> 00:30:28.573
Yeah?

00:30:28.573 --> 00:30:33.010
AUDIENCE: Maybe like delta is
something that [INAUDIBLE]

00:30:33.010 --> 00:30:35.968
whereas beta is a variable that
probably won't happen.

00:30:35.968 --> 00:30:37.218
Like, [INAUDIBLE].

00:30:40.920 --> 00:30:47.560
PROFESSOR: Well, specifically,
these are constant, so think

00:30:47.560 --> 00:30:50.000
of them as being numbers.

00:30:50.000 --> 00:30:52.370
Beta's like a number, like--

00:30:52.370 --> 00:30:57.520
maybe delta is 0.9, and beta's
something like 0.6.

00:30:57.520 --> 00:30:59.230
That's the sort of numbers
people often throw

00:30:59.230 --> 00:31:02.718
around over a month.

00:31:14.870 --> 00:31:16.930
What does this preference
specifically say?

00:31:19.525 --> 00:31:20.914
Yeah?

00:31:20.914 --> 00:31:23.670
AUDIENCE: Seems like it's just
saying that if more importance

00:31:23.670 --> 00:31:29.060
is given to c0, and anything
in the future as a discount

00:31:29.060 --> 00:31:30.040
factor of beta.

00:31:30.040 --> 00:31:34.940
But the further into the future
you go, you go from

00:31:34.940 --> 00:31:39.350
delta to delta squared
so [INAUDIBLE].

00:31:39.350 --> 00:31:42.340
PROFESSOR: Right, but
specifically what it's saying

00:31:42.340 --> 00:31:46.970
is that today versus tomorrow
is very different from

00:31:46.970 --> 00:31:49.580
tomorrow versus day
after or day after

00:31:49.580 --> 00:31:51.870
versus day after that.

00:31:51.870 --> 00:31:57.420
It's saying specifically that
when I offer you a choice

00:31:57.420 --> 00:32:01.250
between today and tomorrow,
you want it today, but you

00:32:01.250 --> 00:32:05.390
don't care as much about day
after versus day after that.

00:32:05.390 --> 00:32:11.080
So beta and delta both numbers
less than 1, then what this

00:32:11.080 --> 00:32:15.610
preference is exactly
saying is that I

00:32:15.610 --> 00:32:16.860
would take one today.

00:32:20.310 --> 00:32:23.850
I'll give up two tomorrow to
get one today, but when I

00:32:23.850 --> 00:32:27.260
compare tomorrow with day after,
I'm not going to take

00:32:27.260 --> 00:32:32.380
one tomorrow instead
of two day after.

00:32:32.380 --> 00:32:35.130
So people are very short--

00:32:35.130 --> 00:32:38.290
they want things now, but they
don't really care about when

00:32:38.290 --> 00:32:39.790
they get it if they
don't get it now.

00:32:43.710 --> 00:32:47.000
Why is that an interesting
set of preferences?

00:32:47.000 --> 00:32:52.020
Well, if you believe those set
of preferences, then this

00:32:52.020 --> 00:32:54.180
behavior seems to start
to make sense.

00:32:54.180 --> 00:33:00.910
So what I really want
is I want tomorrow--

00:33:00.910 --> 00:33:03.650
since I don't care about whether
I consume tomorrow or

00:33:03.650 --> 00:33:08.070
day after, I want tomorrow
to do the saving.

00:33:12.060 --> 00:33:15.370
Today, I don't want to save
because today is much more

00:33:15.370 --> 00:33:17.300
important to me than tomorrow.

00:33:17.300 --> 00:33:20.610
Tomorrow is not that much more
important than day after, so

00:33:20.610 --> 00:33:23.870
if I want some money for day
after, the best way to get

00:33:23.870 --> 00:33:29.430
there is by eating a lot today,
saving a lot tomorrow,

00:33:29.430 --> 00:33:31.450
and then ending up with
the money day after.

00:33:31.450 --> 00:33:39.220
I would rather do that than eat
little today and also a

00:33:39.220 --> 00:33:40.210
little tomorrow.

00:33:40.210 --> 00:33:46.940
I would rather save by binging
today and then waiting, and

00:33:46.940 --> 00:33:50.000
then implementing
saving tomorrow.

00:33:50.000 --> 00:33:52.290
The problem is that when
you get around to

00:33:52.290 --> 00:33:54.235
tomorrow, what happens?

00:33:57.080 --> 00:34:02.210
If your plan is I will save more
tomorrow, I'll eat more

00:34:02.210 --> 00:34:03.740
today, save more tomorrow,
what's the

00:34:03.740 --> 00:34:05.966
problem with that plan?

00:34:05.966 --> 00:34:07.110
AUDIENCE: Tomorrow
becomes today.

00:34:07.110 --> 00:34:08.830
PROFESSOR: Tomorrow
becomes today.

00:34:08.830 --> 00:34:12.600
Once tomorrow becomes today, you
start thinking, OK, well,

00:34:12.600 --> 00:34:14.020
I have the same preferences.

00:34:14.020 --> 00:34:17.889
c0 then becomes tomorrow's c0.

00:34:17.889 --> 00:34:21.870
I want to implement the
same plan tomorrow.

00:34:21.870 --> 00:34:28.590
I want to eat a lot tomorrow,
and get day after to do the

00:34:28.590 --> 00:34:32.239
savings, and you can
keep doing that.

00:34:32.239 --> 00:34:33.692
That's the problem.

00:34:33.692 --> 00:34:40.870
OK, so that's the idea.

00:34:40.870 --> 00:34:43.760
Now do people actually
behave in such a way?

00:34:49.080 --> 00:34:51.380
So here's an experiment.

00:35:01.840 --> 00:35:05.460
Ashraf, Karlan, and Win asked
1,700 subjects in the

00:35:05.460 --> 00:35:10.090
Philippines the following
questions.

00:35:10.090 --> 00:35:13.900
So they asked them, first, would
you prefer 200 pesos now

00:35:13.900 --> 00:35:18.280
or 250 pesos later?

00:35:18.280 --> 00:35:22.840
Some people said I'd prefer
250 later, in

00:35:22.840 --> 00:35:24.220
which case, they stopped.

00:35:24.220 --> 00:35:29.770
If they said that they would
prefer 200 now rather than 250

00:35:29.770 --> 00:35:34.815
in a month, then they were
asked how about 300?

00:35:42.884 --> 00:35:49.070
If they said they'll even take
300, then they were asked how

00:35:49.070 --> 00:35:53.410
much would it take to stop you
from wanting 200 today?

00:35:53.410 --> 00:35:56.430
Somebody might say 400.

00:35:56.430 --> 00:36:02.020
I'll take 200 today
and 400 a month.

00:36:02.020 --> 00:36:08.170
So there are people who could
say 250 I'll take in a month.

00:36:08.170 --> 00:36:10.840
Some people say I'll take
300 in a month.

00:36:10.840 --> 00:36:14.280
Some people will say
name a number.

00:36:14.280 --> 00:36:16.010
So do you see how it goes?

00:36:18.910 --> 00:36:20.775
Then they are given a break.

00:36:20.775 --> 00:36:25.930
They went and wander around,
then came back, and 15 minutes

00:36:25.930 --> 00:36:28.480
later, they were asked the same
set of questions, but

00:36:28.480 --> 00:36:34.580
with one change, which is that
instead of asking them about

00:36:34.580 --> 00:36:38.020
today versus in a month, they
were asked in six months

00:36:38.020 --> 00:36:40.500
versus in seven months.

00:36:43.170 --> 00:36:45.630
Same thing, but notice
what we're doing is

00:36:45.630 --> 00:36:46.915
exactly this exercise.

00:36:46.915 --> 00:36:51.080
We are exactly trying to
pinpoint whether or not people

00:36:51.080 --> 00:36:55.950
have a different view of today
versus tomorrow versus one

00:36:55.950 --> 00:36:59.430
month later at any other
point of time.

00:36:59.430 --> 00:37:05.830
That's exactly the idea, that
am I someone who thinks that

00:37:05.830 --> 00:37:09.300
tomorrow is going to be--

00:37:09.300 --> 00:37:13.340
do I think that tomorrow
