00:55:03.020 --> 00:55:04.460
the future?

00:55:04.460 --> 00:55:05.710
What would you say?

00:55:08.890 --> 00:55:10.920
You all would say in the future
because why would

00:55:10.920 --> 00:55:12.170
[INAUDIBLE]?

00:55:14.890 --> 00:55:18.200
I don't realize I'm going to
do this, so then I have no

00:55:18.200 --> 00:55:21.730
reason to say lock
up my money.

00:55:21.730 --> 00:55:24.850
I should always ask to spend
it in the future.

00:55:27.350 --> 00:55:31.160
You cannot have them being
completely fully

00:55:31.160 --> 00:55:33.680
sophisticated, in which case the
program would not have an

00:55:33.680 --> 00:55:37.360
effect, because they're
sophisticated.

00:55:37.360 --> 00:55:38.530
They don't need the program.

00:55:38.530 --> 00:55:39.890
They'll buy in any case.

00:55:39.890 --> 00:55:43.720
But if you assume that they was
not sophisticated at all,

00:55:43.720 --> 00:55:47.120
then they would say,
look, bring it

00:55:47.120 --> 00:55:48.600
back at planting time.

00:55:48.600 --> 00:55:49.740
I'll buy it then.

00:55:49.740 --> 00:55:51.350
Why would I lockup my money?

00:55:51.350 --> 00:55:55.040
Because I don't understand
that I have this problem.

00:55:55.040 --> 00:55:57.670
So these people must be
halfway between being

00:55:57.670 --> 00:56:00.200
sophisticated and not
being sophisticated.

00:56:00.200 --> 00:56:01.910
They cannot be either
fully sophisticated.

00:56:08.400 --> 00:56:10.360
If they were fully
sophisticated, they would not

00:56:10.360 --> 00:56:13.320
need this program.

00:56:13.320 --> 00:56:16.590
If they were fully
unsophisticated, they would

00:56:16.590 --> 00:56:20.450
not respond to when you offer
them and ask them do you want

00:56:20.450 --> 00:56:23.800
to buy it now or later, they
would all say later, and half

00:56:23.800 --> 00:56:27.330
of them say they want it now
even though they don't need

00:56:27.330 --> 00:56:29.080
the fertilizer now.

00:56:29.080 --> 00:56:32.180
So some of those people must
realize that later, they're

00:56:32.180 --> 00:56:37.390
going to not have the money,
so somehow there is some

00:56:37.390 --> 00:56:42.690
combination of sophistication
and naivete that's driving

00:56:42.690 --> 00:56:43.940
this behavior.

00:56:46.610 --> 00:56:50.640
So one way to look at this
question of how sophisticated

00:56:50.640 --> 00:56:53.380
is go back to that experiment
that we were talking about,

00:56:53.380 --> 00:56:55.520
the Ashraf, Karlan, and Yin.

00:56:55.520 --> 00:56:57.925
What they do is they offer their
subjects a lock-box.

00:56:57.925 --> 00:57:03.940
A lock-box is just a box where
the key is usually kept with

00:57:03.940 --> 00:57:07.720
someone else, so you don't
have access to the key.

00:57:07.720 --> 00:57:09.065
You can put money into it.

00:57:09.065 --> 00:57:12.460
It's just a money box.

00:57:12.460 --> 00:57:16.570
And they were told that
you can set you goal.

00:57:16.570 --> 00:57:24.940
Your goal can be either a date,
so I'll break the box,

00:57:24.940 --> 00:57:29.360
I'll open the box
at Christmas.

00:57:29.360 --> 00:57:30.930
Or it could be an
amount of money.

00:57:30.930 --> 00:57:34.380
I'll open the box once
I have $200 in it.

00:57:34.380 --> 00:57:44.150
So if you look at what people
say, most people want it on a

00:57:44.150 --> 00:57:51.450
date, so a huge fraction say
I want it on Christmas, my

00:57:51.450 --> 00:57:55.060
wife's birthday, my husband's
birthday, my son's birthday,

00:57:55.060 --> 00:57:58.030
my child's graduation,
something like that.

00:57:58.030 --> 00:58:01.960
Then some people have an
amount based goal.

00:58:01.960 --> 00:58:06.140
They say that I need it for
buying a house, so I need this

00:58:06.140 --> 00:58:07.450
much money.

00:58:07.450 --> 00:58:10.390
But most people seemed to
set time-based goals.

00:58:17.070 --> 00:58:22.440
Now, out of 1,7000 people,
only 200 people

00:58:22.440 --> 00:58:25.060
wanted these boxes.

00:58:25.060 --> 00:58:28.210
So not everybody wanted it.

00:58:28.210 --> 00:58:35.300
In fact, only one out of eight,
roughly, wanted one of

00:58:35.300 --> 00:58:36.550
these boxes.

00:58:39.140 --> 00:58:48.570
But among those who did, there's
a massive effect of

00:58:48.570 --> 00:58:49.660
being hyperbolic.

00:58:49.660 --> 00:58:54.680
Hyperbolic are those people who
are patient in the future

00:58:54.680 --> 00:58:57.880
but impatient now.

00:58:57.880 --> 00:59:03.030
Those are the people who really
wanted the lock-boxes,

00:59:03.030 --> 00:59:04.210
so that's what you'd expect.

00:59:04.210 --> 00:59:10.360
You'd expect that somebody who
is fundamentally patient, but

00:59:10.360 --> 00:59:16.070
is impatient right now, is the
one who wants a lock-box

00:59:16.070 --> 00:59:19.580
because they do see the
value of saving.

00:59:19.580 --> 00:59:22.770
They're patient fundamentally,
but they're impatient right

00:59:22.770 --> 00:59:25.010
now in the moment.

00:59:25.010 --> 00:59:27.270
Those are the people who would
want a lock-box, and that's

00:59:27.270 --> 00:59:28.520
exactly what you find.

00:59:28.520 --> 00:59:31.610
You find that the people who
want the lock-box tend to be

00:59:31.610 --> 00:59:36.690
people who are patient in
general, in the future are

00:59:36.690 --> 00:59:39.510
patient, but are less
patient right now.

00:59:39.510 --> 00:59:42.320
They want the lock-box to kind
of bind their hands.

00:59:50.850 --> 00:59:54.450
So they seem to know that
they're hyperbolic, so a lot

00:59:54.450 --> 00:59:57.640
of these people seem to know
they're hyperbolic.

00:59:57.640 --> 01:00:00.190
They seem to realize that they
have this problem, so they're

01:00:00.190 --> 01:00:01.570
not unsophisticated.

01:00:01.570 --> 01:00:04.940
They seem to be relatively aware
of their-- they're not,

01:00:04.940 --> 01:00:06.570
at least, totally
unsophisticated.

01:00:06.570 --> 01:00:08.140
They seem to have some
awareness of their

01:00:08.140 --> 01:00:11.640
self-control problem.

01:00:11.640 --> 01:00:15.320
The other striking thing is
only women are effected.

01:00:15.320 --> 01:00:21.120
Men don't seem to understand
they have this problem, even

01:00:21.120 --> 01:00:23.080
though they do, actually.

01:00:23.080 --> 01:00:26.760
So women seem to understand
they have a problem.

01:00:26.760 --> 01:00:29.275
Men also have the same problem,
but they don't seem

01:00:29.275 --> 01:00:31.000
to understand it.

01:00:31.000 --> 01:00:36.190
Now, here's another experiment,
last experiment we

01:00:36.190 --> 01:00:43.170
will talk about, which gives a
different take to this men

01:00:43.170 --> 01:00:44.420
versus women question.

01:00:47.040 --> 01:00:52.820
We've been talking a lot about
this kind of hyperbolic view,

01:00:52.820 --> 01:00:57.340
which says that I'm worried that
I won't be able to save.

01:00:57.340 --> 01:01:00.690
An alternative view of why
people don't save is they feel

01:01:00.690 --> 01:01:05.160
like I want to save, but I
know that I can't because

01:01:05.160 --> 01:01:07.450
somebody else will come and
take the money away.

01:01:10.800 --> 01:01:14.800
My husband will spend it, or my
brother will come and beg

01:01:14.800 --> 01:01:17.040
me money, and I'll have to give
it to him or something.

01:01:17.040 --> 01:01:21.940
So one other reason for not
saving, which is related, and

01:01:21.940 --> 01:01:27.500
one reason why women might want
a lock-box more might not

01:01:27.500 --> 01:01:29.740
be because just that
they're hyperbolic.

01:01:29.740 --> 01:01:33.540
They might also worry about the
fact that their husbands

01:01:33.540 --> 01:01:38.710
will just take away the money,
and that might explain their

01:01:38.710 --> 01:01:42.380
demand for lock-boxes, that they
want to keep the money

01:01:42.380 --> 01:01:45.580
away from their husband and say
that we can't get at the

01:01:45.580 --> 01:01:47.210
money right now.

01:01:47.210 --> 01:01:52.270
So this is an experiment
in a bank.

01:01:56.090 --> 01:01:58.280
This one was done by Simone
Schaner, who was a

01:01:58.280 --> 01:02:02.320
PhD Student at MIT.

01:02:02.320 --> 01:02:07.910
So this is a bank, and
basically, she invited a bunch

01:02:07.910 --> 01:02:12.440
of married couples to the bank
and said do you want to open

01:02:12.440 --> 01:02:13.230
an account.

01:02:13.230 --> 01:02:18.315
And the accounts she offered
had came in three types.

01:02:18.315 --> 01:02:24.730
I mean, everybody was offered
one joint account for two

01:02:24.730 --> 01:02:29.690
spouses, one wife's account,
and one husband's account.

01:02:29.690 --> 01:02:32.410
The reason why they did that,
she was trying to get at this

01:02:32.410 --> 01:02:36.130
idea that maybe if I have a
joint account with my husband,

01:02:36.130 --> 01:02:39.910
that's not very good because
he can take out the money.

01:02:39.910 --> 01:02:42.490
If I want to have an account,
I want full control of it.

01:02:48.460 --> 01:02:52.700
So what she's interested in is
this question, are people

01:02:52.700 --> 01:02:55.550
sufficiently aware of this
problem that they're willing

01:02:55.550 --> 01:02:58.500
to give up a high return
account to

01:02:58.500 --> 01:02:59.750
have their own account?

01:03:03.460 --> 01:03:07.040
So the design of the experiment
is one where,

01:03:07.040 --> 01:03:10.940
sometimes, randomly, the joint
account has the highest

01:03:10.940 --> 01:03:14.420
interest rate, and your own
account has a very low

01:03:14.420 --> 01:03:15.990
interest rate.

01:03:15.990 --> 01:03:18.720
And what she's interested in is
whether you would give up

01:03:18.720 --> 01:03:23.400
getting a high interest
rate account to

01:03:23.400 --> 01:03:25.720
get your own account.

01:03:25.720 --> 01:03:28.320
So for the whole family, it
would be better to get a joint

01:03:28.320 --> 01:03:33.100
account in terms of returns.

01:03:33.100 --> 01:03:38.470
So the returns can vary between
0% to 10%, so you

01:03:38.470 --> 01:03:41.620
could be getting 10% on the
account instead of zero, but

01:03:41.620 --> 01:03:46.360
you might choose zero because
you don't want your wife or

01:03:46.360 --> 01:03:49.335
husband to get at it.

01:03:59.700 --> 01:04:00.910
So I'll skip this.

01:04:00.910 --> 01:04:02.310
This just explain the point.

01:04:02.310 --> 01:04:05.890
The point is that people got
different accounts offered, so

01:04:05.890 --> 01:04:08.560
some people were offered a
joint account with the

01:04:08.560 --> 01:04:14.040
interest rate zero, a man's
account with interest rate

01:04:14.040 --> 01:04:19.640
zero, but a joint account
with interest rate two.

01:04:19.640 --> 01:04:23.680
So this is sort of just to
understand the experiment, you

01:04:23.680 --> 01:04:28.630
might be someone who gets the
joint account interest rates

01:04:28.630 --> 01:04:32.310
could be 10, but the man's
account interest rate could be

01:04:32.310 --> 01:04:34.710
zero, and the woman's account
interest rate could be two.

01:04:44.160 --> 01:04:49.600
So what's in the squares are
the excess interest rate on

01:04:49.600 --> 01:04:55.560
the account you're choosing, so
maybe you choose an account

01:04:55.560 --> 01:04:58.650
which gives you 4%.

01:04:58.650 --> 01:05:01.080
You could have gotten the best
account you could have got

01:05:01.080 --> 01:05:02.640
would have interest
rate of 10.

01:05:02.640 --> 01:05:05.390
Your excess interest rate is
negative in that case.

01:05:05.390 --> 01:05:08.530
You are getting a -6%
on the interest.

01:05:08.530 --> 01:05:11.350
So the question here, the reason
why this experiment is

01:05:11.350 --> 01:05:14.920
interesting, you're trying to
figure out do people give up

01:05:14.920 --> 01:05:21.850
getting lots of extra money
to make sure that somebody

01:05:21.850 --> 01:05:23.477
doesn't have access
to their account.

01:05:31.110 --> 01:05:34.360
So first thing she did
was to figure out--

01:05:38.320 --> 01:05:40.350
she'll administer
these questions

01:05:40.350 --> 01:05:42.426
where they ask them--

01:05:42.426 --> 01:05:44.890
it's kind of like the questions
we were asking.

01:05:44.890 --> 01:05:56.190
How much money would you give
up today for 290 Kenyan

01:05:56.190 --> 01:05:59.940
shillings tomorrow?

01:05:59.940 --> 01:06:03.030
So these are questions basically
aimed to measure how

01:06:03.030 --> 01:06:06.000
impatient people.

01:06:06.000 --> 01:06:10.310
Would you take 20 today or 200
tomorrow, and if you say 20

01:06:10.310 --> 01:06:12.665
today, you're very impatient,
obviously.

01:06:12.665 --> 01:06:15.650
So that's the kind of question
she was asking.

01:06:15.650 --> 01:06:21.520
So what she did, by using that,
what she figured out was

01:06:21.520 --> 01:06:24.380
who are the couples who
are well matched.

01:06:24.380 --> 01:06:28.570
So if I'm impatient and my wife
is impatient, that's no

01:06:28.570 --> 01:06:31.340
problem because neither
of us want to save.

01:06:31.340 --> 01:06:36.760
So I don't have to tie my
husband's hands or my wife's

01:06:36.760 --> 01:06:42.730
hands because I have the same
preferences as she does, and

01:06:42.730 --> 01:06:45.810
therefore, if she wants to
spend, I also want to spend.

01:06:48.730 --> 01:06:52.450
Then there are couple which are
both parties are patient,

01:06:52.450 --> 01:06:57.450
so if one wants to save, the
other wants to save.

01:07:03.240 --> 01:07:06.610
And then there are people
who were given--

01:07:06.610 --> 01:07:08.240
the couples which
are ill matched.

01:07:08.240 --> 01:07:11.630
Ill matched couples are where
one says I want to save now,

01:07:11.630 --> 01:07:14.880
the other says I want
to spend now.

01:07:14.880 --> 01:07:16.670
So they're ill matched
couples.

01:07:16.670 --> 01:07:20.960
Now, it's the ill matched
couples that are going to

01:07:20.960 --> 01:07:24.510
choose accounts that
have low returns.

01:07:24.510 --> 01:07:29.940
If you're well matched, it
really doesn't matter who's

01:07:29.940 --> 01:07:33.340
name the account is in because
we have the same objectives.

01:07:33.340 --> 01:07:35.850
We both want to spend now.

01:07:35.850 --> 01:07:38.060
We both want to spend
in the future.

01:07:38.060 --> 01:07:40.980
Whatever we want to do,
we both want to do.

01:07:40.980 --> 01:07:44.030
But if one of the spouses is
patient, and the other's

01:07:44.030 --> 01:07:46.170
impatient, you have a problem.

01:07:46.170 --> 01:07:48.910
Now, it turns out, she went
with the hypothesis that

01:07:48.910 --> 01:07:51.300
she'll find that only the
men are impatient.

01:07:51.300 --> 01:07:55.760
Turns out it was about 50/50,
about men and women are

01:07:55.760 --> 01:08:00.280
equally likely to be less
patient than their spouse.

01:08:00.280 --> 01:08:04.500
But a lot of these households
were ill matched, so a lot of

01:08:04.500 --> 01:08:07.650
the households had one spouse
who was very patient and the

01:08:07.650 --> 01:08:10.700
other spouse who was
very impatient.

01:08:10.700 --> 01:08:13.930
That's a setting where you'd
imagine going back to the

01:08:13.930 --> 01:08:18.520
issue we were raising, as we
said, maybe people don't save

01:08:18.520 --> 01:08:23.220
because they feel that
they can't save.

01:08:23.220 --> 01:08:28.220
If they try to save, the spouse
will just spend it.

01:08:28.220 --> 01:08:30.609
So if one of the spouses is
patient, but the other's

01:08:30.609 --> 01:08:33.970
impatient, the impatient
spouse kind of has an

01:08:33.970 --> 01:08:36.760
advantage because once the
money's spent, it's gone.

01:08:39.460 --> 01:08:42.779
The patient spouse will keep
guarding the money, but the

01:08:42.779 --> 01:08:46.240
impatient spouse, all she has
to do is to spend it.

01:08:46.240 --> 01:08:50.370
Once it's spent, it's gone, so
in a sense, the impatience

01:08:50.370 --> 01:08:53.710
spouse always has
an advantage.

01:08:53.710 --> 01:08:56.910
So you're always fighting
against the impatience spouse.

01:08:56.910 --> 01:09:01.350
The patient spouse is always
trying to save it and can't do

01:09:01.350 --> 01:09:04.380
much about it once the
money's spent.

01:09:04.380 --> 01:09:07.529
But as a patient spouse
is always--

01:09:07.529 --> 01:09:09.430
if she's saved it through today,
she has to save it

01:09:09.430 --> 01:09:10.399
through tomorrow.

01:09:10.399 --> 01:09:15.529
In some sense, it's kind of
an asymmetric problem.

01:09:15.529 --> 01:09:19.279
So what she's looking for is
what happens to these ill

01:09:19.279 --> 01:09:20.529
matched couples.

01:09:25.270 --> 01:09:28.929
So this is sort of just to give
a sense of how many are

01:09:28.929 --> 01:09:29.380
ill matched.

01:09:29.380 --> 01:09:30.114
Yeah, Melissa?

01:09:30.114 --> 01:09:31.364
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]?

01:09:35.926 --> 01:09:38.686
PROFESSOR: We'll be done
in two minutes.

01:09:38.686 --> 01:09:42.160
So this is a graph of
ill matched couples.

01:09:49.480 --> 01:09:51.520
A lot of these are at zero.

01:09:51.520 --> 01:09:55.470
You can see zero means you have
the same discount factor.

01:09:55.470 --> 01:09:57.080
You're equally patient.

01:09:57.080 --> 01:09:59.920
But you can see that there are
people who are difference of

01:09:59.920 --> 01:10:06.000
-0.5, so that means
that I want it--

01:10:06.000 --> 01:10:12.300
my discount factor is maybe
0.9, and my spouse is 0.4.

01:10:12.300 --> 01:10:14.640
And look, it's basically
symmetrical.

01:10:14.640 --> 01:10:16.290
Men and women are
not different.

01:10:16.290 --> 01:10:19.450
It's just one of the
spouses is more

01:10:19.450 --> 01:10:20.840
impatient than the other.

01:10:20.840 --> 01:10:22.160
And then what she looks at--

01:10:22.160 --> 01:10:24.970
I'll skip these and show
you the picture.

01:10:24.970 --> 01:10:29.530
So on the horizontal axis
is excess interest rate.

01:10:29.530 --> 01:10:30.810
How much are you giving up?

01:10:36.800 --> 01:10:39.500
When the wife's account has,
let's say, the highest

01:10:39.500 --> 01:10:43.540
interest rate over the
other account--

01:10:47.950 --> 01:10:59.010
what fraction of the people
use the account more?

01:10:59.010 --> 01:11:02.420
And you can see that basically,
for well matched

01:11:02.420 --> 01:11:06.880
couples, the shared saving in
that account is clearly

01:11:06.880 --> 01:11:08.720
increasing with interest rate.

01:11:08.720 --> 01:11:10.570
If the interest rate
is higher, you save

01:11:10.570 --> 01:11:11.930
more in that account.

01:11:11.930 --> 01:11:16.260
For ill matched couples, they
see no relationship.

01:11:16.260 --> 01:11:20.800
You don't save more because the
account is more rewarding.

01:11:20.800 --> 01:11:21.100
Why?

01:11:21.100 --> 01:11:24.750
Because it doesn't matter if
it's more rewarding or not.

01:11:24.750 --> 01:11:28.000
You just don't want that on
the other guy to have that

01:11:28.000 --> 01:11:31.300
access to that account.

01:11:31.300 --> 01:11:37.000
So ill matched couples don't
react to the interest rate.

01:11:37.000 --> 01:11:38.800
Their priority is
something else.

01:11:38.800 --> 01:11:40.390
They want their own account.

01:11:40.390 --> 01:11:42.760
Doesn't matter whether that's
a low interest account.

01:11:42.760 --> 01:11:46.890
The well matched couples, you
see this, and you can see the

01:11:46.890 --> 01:11:49.770
same thing for the
joint accounts.

01:11:49.770 --> 01:11:52.490
The joint accounts, again, it's
the same question, excess

01:11:52.490 --> 01:11:55.850
interest rate, share saving.

01:11:55.850 --> 01:11:58.970
The well matched couples, as the
interest rate goes up, you

01:11:58.970 --> 01:12:01.200
save more in that account.

01:12:01.200 --> 01:12:03.180
In the badly matched couples,
it doesn't matter.

01:12:03.180 --> 01:12:05.050
Interest rate doesn't matter.

01:12:05.050 --> 01:12:08.490
If you're badly matched, you
choose the one that you will

